    st.subheader("Executive Summary")

    st.markdown("""
    ### Dataset & Prediction Task

    This project analyzes anonymized medical records from approximately **one million COVID-19 patients
    in Mexico**, sourced from the General Directorate of Epidemiology of the Mexican Ministry of Health.
    Each patient record contains **16 features**: the patient's age, biological sex, and the presence or
    absence of 14 clinical indicators — including whether the patient was hospitalized, tested
    COVID-positive, and whether they had pre-existing conditions such as pneumonia, diabetes,
    hypertension, COPD, obesity, cardiovascular disease, chronic renal disease, asthma,
    immunosuppression, or tobacco use. The target variable, **DEATH**, records whether each patient
    ultimately survived (0) or died (1).

    ### Why This Matters

    Predicting which COVID-19 patients face the highest mortality risk is not an academic exercise — it is
    a practical tool for **hospital triage and resource allocation**. During pandemic surges, intensive care
    beds, ventilators, and specialist attention are scarce. A reliable risk-stratification model can help
    clinicians identify patients who need aggressive early intervention, and it can guide hospital
    administrators in distributing limited resources to where they will save the most lives. Understanding
    *which* factors drive mortality — and by how much — also informs public health messaging and
    vaccination prioritization strategies.

    ### Approach

    Because the raw dataset is heavily imbalanced (roughly 10 survivors for every 1 death), we created a
    balanced working sample of 10,000 patients (5,000 deceased, 5,000 survivors) to ensure that models
    learn to predict both classes effectively. We then trained and compared five models of increasing
    complexity: **Logistic Regression** (interpretable baseline), **Decision Tree** (transparent rule-based),
    **Random Forest** (ensemble), **LightGBM** (gradient boosted trees), and a **Multi-Layer Perceptron
    neural network**. Each model (except Logistic Regression and MLP) was tuned via 5-fold
    cross-validated grid search using the F1 score, with a held-out 30% test set reserved for final
    evaluation. All models use `random_state=42` for full reproducibility.

    ### Key Findings

    **Age is by far the most powerful predictor of COVID-19 mortality.** Patients who died were
    substantially older on average than survivors, and every model — from logistic regression to gradient
    boosting — ranks age as the dominant feature. **Pneumonia at time of admission** is the second
    strongest signal: patients presenting with pneumonia face dramatically higher mortality risk,
    suggesting that severe respiratory involvement at intake should trigger immediate escalation.
    Cardiovascular disease, chronic renal disease, and hospitalization status also contribute meaningfully.

    Among all models, **LightGBM achieved the best overall performance**, with the highest F1 score and
    AUC-ROC on the held-out test set. Random Forest followed closely. SHAP analysis confirmed that the
    model's decision logic aligns with established clinical knowledge — older patients with pneumonia and
    cardiovascular disease are flagged as high-risk, while younger patients without severe comorbidities
    are predicted to survive. This clinical face-validity is essential for any model that might be deployed in
    a real healthcare setting.

    We recommend deploying LightGBM with an **optimized probability threshold** (tuned via Youden's J
    statistic) rather than the default 0.5 cutoff, because in a clinical context, failing to identify a
    high-risk patient (false negative) is far more costly than flagging an extra patient for monitoring (false
    positive). SHAP explanations should accompany every prediction to ensure transparency and clinician
    trust.
    """)

